</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C309EEC62F73FFF84EAFF989FD7AF972" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BACBD4D2F73FFF84EAFF989FD7AF972" blockId="9.[151,1436,1445,1758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F73FFF84EAFF989FE27F9E2" bold="true" box="[199,504,1589,1614]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F73FFF84C6AF989FD66F9E1" box="[514,697,1589,1614]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peruana">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F73FFF84C6AF989FD66F9E1" box="[514,697,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bachia peruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to southwestern 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F73FFF84A62F989FB5FF9E2" box="[1034,1152,1589,1614]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="9" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, occurring in 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F73FFF84B4DF989FAB6F9E2" box="[1317,1385,1589,1614]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F73FFF84EFFF9E6FF14F9DD" box="[151,203,1626,1649]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="1328A1C82F73FFF84E88F9E5FEF6F9DE" box="[224,297,1625,1650]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F304FDDD2F73FFF84F02F9E5FE6EF9DE" box="[362,433,1625,1650]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F73FFF84D54F9E6FC6DF9DE" box="[828,946,1626,1650]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="49D773AF2F73FFF84D9DF9E6FBF1F9DE" box="[1013,1070,1626,1650]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Acre</collectingRegion>
, restricted to the Juruá–Envira interfluvium. 
<taxonomicName id="4C13C6CE2F73FFF84F5DF9C1FE30F939" box="[309,495,1661,1686]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peruana">
<emphasis id="B967615F2F73FFF84F5DF9C1FE30F939" box="[309,495,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bachia peruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial and diurnal (Schlüter 
<emphasis id="B967615F2F73FFF84DEEF9C2FC1CF93A" box="[902,963,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
2004), inhabits primary terra firme and flooded forests (Pantoja &amp; Fraga 2012). Dixon (1973) reported the species “under rotting logs and in loose soil beneath decaying vegetation in coffee groves”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
